<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53cf682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:5.</label.designator><headtext>Privilege against self-incrimination—Unlawfully obtained statement as impeachment</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The United State Supreme Court, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971127006" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief3e73b27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Harris v. New York</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a123107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] held that statements procured in violation of <ital>Miranda</ital>, which are inadmissible to establish guilt, could still be used for impeachment purposes. <eos/><bos/>Later, the Court applied this rule in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1980116771" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief3f5e127fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Jenkins v. Anderson</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a123117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] where the defendant testified that he acted in self-defense. <eos/><bos/>The trial court permitted the prosecutor to use defendant&apos;s silence during the two-week period between the killing and his surrender for the purpose of impeachment. <eos/><bos/>In affirming the lower courts, the United States Supreme Court held that <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief406f827fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Doyle v. Ohio</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a123127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] did not apply and that his pre-arrest silence could be used for impeachment purposes. <eos/><bos/>Again in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1980116773" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief4132d27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Anderson v. Charles,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a14a207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] the court upheld using defendant&apos;s statements for impeachment because his testimony included statements which were not included in his earlier statements to police made after a <ital>Miranda</ital> warning.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Likewise, Georgia courts have allowed defendant&apos;s voluntary statements secured in violation of <ital>Miranda</ital> to be used at trial for impeachment if the defendant testifies.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a14a217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] In such a circumstance, the trial court must give a limiting instruction to the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a14a227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] As the Court of Appeals explained in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971128573" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief43cae27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Colbert v. State</ital></cite.query>:[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a171307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7<page no="91"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>If on the trial of his case the defendant takes the witness stand and swears to a state of facts contrary to his prior statements, they may be given in evidence solely for purposes of impeachment, the burden being on the court to caution the jury that such evidence is to be considered only for the purpose of assessing the defendant&apos;s credibility and not to establish his guilt of the offense for which he is on trial; however, where the evidence is not offered solely for this purpose nor does the trial judge instruct the jury to consider it solely for purposes of impeachment, its admission is error.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext></para></display.quote><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court does not need to conduct a <ital>Jackson Denno</ital> hearing if the defendant&apos;s statement is used only for impeachment,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a171317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] but the trial judge must still determine if the defendant voluntarily made the statement.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a171327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Court-ordered psychiatric examinations which are intended to be used to produce evidence against an accused, such as those used during the penalty phase of a trial[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a198407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] or those related to an insanity plea,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a198417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>] violate an accused&apos;s privilege against self-incrimination. <eos/><bos/>Although an accused does not waive his privilege against self-incrimination by raising the insanity defense, the introduction of psychiatric testimony in support of the defense does constitute a waiver of the privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a198427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>] Thus, if the accused presents expert psychiatric testimony at trial to support his insanity defense, he must also submit to a court-ordered psychiatric examination to give the prosecution an opportunity for rebuttal.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a198437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13<page no="92"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Supreme Court held in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4885d27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Presnell v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2a1bf507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14</footnote.reference>] that a court-ordered psychiatric examination determining an accused&apos;s competency to stand trial did not violate his privilege against self-incrimination because his statements were only used to determine competency. <eos/><bos/>Additionally, the court found that questioning the psychiatrist, who could use the accused&apos;s statements made during the competency evaluation as the basis of his opinion, would not violate the defendant&apos;s privilege against self-incrimination.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2a1bf517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">15</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic2a123107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971127006" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief3ec1d27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. New York, 401 U.S. 222, 91 S. Ct. 643, 28 L. Ed. 2d 1 (1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a123117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1980116771" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief3fac327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Jenkins v. Anderson, 447 U.S. 231, 100 S. Ct. 2124, 65 L. Ed. 2d 86 (1980)</cite.query>, followed in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1982113055" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief3fac367fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fletcher v. Weir, 455 U.S. 603, 102 S. Ct. 1309, 71 L. Ed. 2d 490 (1982)</cite.query>, where the court held that the defendant&apos;s silence could be used to impeach him as a witness despite police failing to give a <ital>Miranda</ital> warning to him.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a123127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief40bda27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Doyle v. Ohio, 426 U.S. 610, 96 S. Ct. 2240, 49 L. Ed. 2d 91 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a14a207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1980116773" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief4180f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Anderson v. Charles, 447 U.S. 404, 100 S. Ct. 2180, 65 L. Ed. 2d 222 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a14a217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1976135371" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief421d327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Alexander v. State, 138 Ga. App. 618, 226 S.E.2d 807 (1976)</cite.query> (citing <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971127006" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief4244427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. New York, 401 U.S. 222, 91 S. Ct. 643, 28 L. Ed. 2d 1 (1971)</cite.query>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1995055703" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4244467fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. State, 265 Ga. 84, 453 S.E.2d 716 (1995)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="2004516909" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4244497fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Mayberry v. State, 267 Ga. App. 620, 600 S.E.2d 703 (2004)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a14a227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971128573" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief42b9727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Colbert v. State, 124 Ga. App. 283, 183 S.E.2d 476 (1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="2005323152" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief432ea27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Eldridge v. State, 270 Ga. App. 84, 86, 606 S.E.2d 95 (2004)</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[a] prior inconsistent statement is <page no="91"/>admissible for impeachment purposes even if <ital>Miranda</ital> warnings were not given, although the trial court in this circumstance has a duty to give appropriate limiting instructions”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a171307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7<page no="91"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1971128573" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief43f1f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Colbert v. State, 124 Ga. App. 283, 183 S.E.2d 476 (1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a171317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1979126949" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief44b5427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Scott v. State, 243 Ga. 233, 253 S.E.2d 698 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="2003874286" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4503627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Robles v. State, 277 Ga. 415, 589 S.E.2d 566 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a171327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1980121887" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4578927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Green v. State, 154 Ga. App. 295, 267 S.E.2d 898 (1980)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1998108743" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4578957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Cook v. State, 269 Ga. 460, 499 S.E.2d 887 (1998)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="2003874286" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4578987fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Robles v. State, 277 Ga. 415, 589 S.E.2d 566 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a198407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1981121562" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief463be27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Estelle v. Smith, 451 U.S. 454, 101 S. Ct. 1866, 68 L. Ed. 2d 359 (1981)</cite.query>, wherein the United States Supreme Court found that admission of a psychiatrist&apos;s testimony on the issue of a defendant&apos;s future dangerousness at the penalty phase of a capital case when the testimony was the result of an in-custody court-ordered competency examination infringed the defendant&apos;s Fifth Amendment constitutional guarantee against self-incrimination.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a198417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1984157094" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief468a027fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ingram v. State, 253 Ga. 622, 323 S.E.2d 801 (1984)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1986153865" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief468a057fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. State, 256 Ga. 350, 352, 349 S.E.2d 374 (1986)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1987020350" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief46b1107fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hicks v. State, 256 Ga. 715, 352 S.E.2d 762 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a198427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1986153865" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4726427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. State, 256 Ga. 350, 352, 349 S.E.2d 374 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1981121562" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief4774627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Estelle v. Smith, 451 U.S. 454, 101 S. Ct. 1866, 68 L. Ed. 2d 359 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a198437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13<page no="92"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1997121778" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief47e9927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Daniel v. State, 268 Ga. 9, 485 S.E.2d 734 (1997)</cite.query> (citing <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1992049813" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief47e9957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Lynd v. State, 262 Ga. 58, 64, 414 S.E.2d 5 (1992)</cite.query>).<eos/><page no="92"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a1bf507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief48d3f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Presnell v. State, 241 Ga. 49, 243 S.E.2d 496 (1978)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d in part</case.history> on other grounds, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1978139540" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief48d3f57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">439 U.S. 14, 99 S. Ct. 235, 58 L. Ed. 2d 207 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1986138259" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4949227fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Cannon v. State, 179 Ga. App. 142, 345 S.E.2d 623 (1986)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1986153865" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4949257fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. State, 256 Ga. 350, 352, 349 S.E.2d 374 (1986)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The problem of a limited waiver by the defendant in these cases is considered in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1987031411" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief4949287fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Motes v. State, 256 Ga. 831, 353 S.E.2d 348 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2a1bf517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief49e5627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Presnell v. State, 241 Ga. 49, 56, 243 S.E.2d 496 (1978)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d in part</case.history> on other grounds, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018118" w-serial-number="1978139540" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ief49e5657fbf11ea988285db8533e975">439 U.S. 14, 99 S. Ct. 235, 58 L. Ed. 2d 207 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 4:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
